'''Recreant''' has been in use in English as an adjective, meaning "confessing oneself to be overcome or vanquished," since the [[14th century]], from [[Old French]] ''recreant'' "yielding, giving," 
from a verb ''recroire'' "to yield in a trial by combat, surrender allegiance," from ''re-'' "again, back" + ''croire'' "entrust, believe," from L. ''credere''.

As a noun, "one who yields in combat, coward, faint-hearted person" is first recorded from the [[15th century]]. The modern sense of  "unfaithful to duty" is modern, first attested in 1643 ([[OED]]).

